This case tests the inhomogeneous boundary condition options. The parameters are the same 
as for the Christesen benchmark case 1, E=0.001, Ra=65000, Pr=1, Pm=5 with no inner core, I_Nic=1. 
The resolution is set to i_N=128, i_L=128, i_M=128, with i_Mp=1i and d_rratio=0.35. 
The Boussinesq option is used, with b_diff_profile = false, so the diffusivity = 1 everywhere.

The new feature is that b_inhombc_C = .true. and  b_inhom_magPol = .true. This means that the 
boundary codensities are set by whatever is in codBC.txt.in and the poloidal magnetic
field at the boundaries is set to whatever is in mag_PolBC.txt.in. In this particular run
the codensity is only set at the outer boundary, because the first integer in both rows is 2,
which correponds to the outer boundary, 1 indicating the inner boundary. There are only two
non-zero entries in codBC.txt.in, so the applied boundary condition has non-zero values
only for l=1, m=0 and l=1, m=1. The resulting pattern can be seen by plotting the codensity
(entropy) of the state files at te outer boundary. Of course, and desired comonation of
spherical harmonics can be applied, at either the inner or outer boundary or both.

Similarly the file  mag_PolBC.txt.in supplies the poloidal spherical harmonic coefficients
required for the outer or inner boundary poloidal magnetic field. In this particular run,
only outer boundary values are non-zero, because all rows of  mag_PolBC.txt.in have first 
entry 2. The values for this run correspond to the Earth's magnetic field in the year 2000,
the 2nd and 3rd values being the corresponding l and m values and the 4th and 5th to the
real and imaginary parts of the corresponding harmonics, up to degree 13.  A matlab script
magnetic_BCs.m is supplied which generates the poloidal harmonics from the gauus coefficients
which are read in from a file earthgauss_2000.txt. The script is included in the Directory 
Matlab_scripts. The comments in this script explain the relation between the real Gauss
coefficients and the poloidal spherical harmonic coefficients. Note however there is an 
arbitrary scaling factor for the strength of the poloidal field. This depends on how the
dimensionless magnetic field unit is chosen to compare with the dimensional geomagnetic
field units. This is not entirely straightforward, as it is not possible for all the
parameters to have earthlike values. For example, you could set the rotation rate, the diffusivity
and the density to have earthlike values and hence derive the unit of magnetic field from its usual
definition. However, a better way to choose the magnetic field unit might be to get the Alfven speed
right, as derived from torsional wave observations. 
